comments.body:
@aam not sure I follow -- the JSON is only ever read/written by this class itself. It's a map of String->String by design. If it's not, there's been a programmer error.

Personally I prefer keeping the type as <String,String> and casting here as it indicates that this is an intentional file format decision and this isn't just arbitrary JSON. If that assumption ever changes, we can update the code.

That leaves the question of what happens if the file is some form of JSON that isn't purely String->String. I don't know that we should treat that any differently from any other sort of file corruption (e.g. replacing the contents with a PNG).

